   DirectedInfinity[1]]]], "Output",
 CellMargins->{{20, 5}, {6, 10}},
 ShowCellLabel->False,ExpressionUUID->"c5fcfde4-335b-4076-99da-f4568e6ab503"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The whole post in one animation. Left: ",
 StyleBox["Monte Carlo",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " points scattered at random clump and leave gaps. Right: ",
 StyleBox["Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote]",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " low-discrepancy points fill the same square evenly. Below: the error of a \
sample integral as the points accumulate \[LongDash] Monte Carlo crawls down \
the ",
 StyleBox["1/\[Sqrt]N",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " line while Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] plunges along ",
 StyleBox["1/N",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 ". Generated near the end of this post with one call to ",
 StyleBox["heroAnimation[]",
  FontFamily->"Source Code Pro",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0.153, 0.51, 0.64]],
 "."
}], "Text",
 FontSize->12,
 FontColor->GrayLevel[
  0.4],ExpressionUUID->"ddb1628b-f26a-4748-b3bf-affd5307b9ed"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Almost every number a Bayesian reports \[LongDash] a posterior mean, a \
credible interval, a predicted drug concentration \[LongDash] is secretly an ",
 StyleBox["integral",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " over the space of unknown parameters. This post is about computing those \
integrals up to an order of magnitude more cheaply."
}], "Text",
 FontSize->16,
 FontColor->GrayLevel[
  0.2],ExpressionUUID->"97522650-02b9-4892-af06-0365793b78cd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The default tool is ",
 StyleBox["Monte Carlo",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ": average the integrand over random samples. It is universal and \
assumption-free, but its error shrinks only as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["N", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1", "/", "2"}]], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"38b88f7d-7aef-4a46-94f7-980879eb734d"],
 " \[LongDash] one more correct digit costs a hundred times more samples. ",
 StyleBox["Quasi-Monte Carlo (QMC)",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " keeps the same averaging but replaces the random sample with a \
deterministic ",
 StyleBox["low-discrepancy sequence",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " (Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote], Halton) engineered to fill space evenly. For \
smooth integrands the error then falls almost as fast as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"O", "(", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox["N", 
      RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], 
     SuperscriptBox[
      RowBox[{"(", "log", " ", "N", ")"}], "d"]}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]], 
  "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->"d6d0f592-3709-4812-a656-4cc2ee0e491e"],
 " \[LongDash] nearly a full power of ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " better."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d3ff4fbf-c838-45d6-9838-e61610ff5d5e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We test that promise on a genuine inference problem: a six-parameter \
pharmacokinetic model fit to the classic ",
 StyleBox["Theophylline",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " data. We build Halton and Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] from scratch, set up the \
posterior, contrast it with classical curve-fitting, and measure the \
convergence. The headline, on a real-data posterior: Monte-Carlo slopes near ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"-", "0.5"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "27c8d560-a64f-4222-8dfb-d8faf1d959e3"],
 " against Sobol\[CloseCurlyQuote] slopes near ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"-", "0.95"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "4c6625c3-31fa-49b0-9dd8-7ea60800707e"],
 ", and a 2\[Times]\[Dash]18\[Times] saving in expensive model evaluations."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"cce5ed03-9d6a-4b65-bfd6-7f47dd1b495d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["How to read this:",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " every section opens with the plain idea, then the equations, the runnable \
Wolfram Language, and the measured numbers. All figures are pre-rendered \
\[LongDash] the post reads straight through \[LongDash] and every code cell \
runs if you load the attached package."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d399d6b3-7b0b-4051-8037-2c0e7658b347"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Setup", "Section",
 FontColor->RGBColor[
  0.153, 0.51, 0.64],ExpressionUUID->"8403355c-8a21-4059-bd31-0cdd3875342e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Skip this if you only want to read.",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " To run the code, put the attached package ",
 StyleBox["qmc_bayes_helpers.wl",
  FontFamily->"Source Code Pro",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0.153, 0.51, 0.64]],
 " next to the notebook and evaluate the three cells below once. They define \
the generators, the pharmacokinetic model, the data, the priors, and the \
posterior that every later section reuses."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9c0ff180-1105-4e1a-9aa5-f11117a84bcc"],

Cell["\<\
SetDirectory[NotebookDirectory[]];
Get[\"qmc_bayes_helpers.wl\"];\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"bef4fbd8-32d7-477e-8748-582ab57e1723"],

Cell["\<\
(* Lognormal-prior medians and log-scale SDs for {ka,CL,V1,Q,V2,sigma} *)
priorMedians = {1.5, 3.0, 35.0, 2.0, 25.0, 1.0};
priorLogSD   = {0.6, 0.5, 0.5, 0.7, 0.7, 0.5};

(* Real data: Theophylline Subject 1 (single 320 mg oral dose) *)
theoph = LoadTheoph[];
subj1  = SelectSubject[theoph, 1];\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"3096b14b-f638-4c87-8d96-4e258184903b"],

Cell["\<\
(* The Bayesian problem and its Laplace-Gaussian posterior *)
pkProblem = BayesProblem[subj1[\"dose\"], subj1[\"t\"], subj1[\"c\"],
   priorMedians, priorLogSD];
pkLaplace = LaplacePosterior[pkProblem];\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"62866b79-30ef-4eb0-a7f9-c9f6648626f9"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["1.  The square-root wall", "Section",
 FontColor->RGBColor[
  0.153, 0.51, 0.64],ExpressionUUID->"58e89cb0-a552-42d1-b647-6d7f9889dcda"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Want the average of something over a space too big to enumerate? Sample it. \
Throw ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontFamily->"Times",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " random points, average the values. This Monte-Carlo estimate works in any \
dimension with no smoothness assumptions \[LongDash] which is why it is \
everywhere. The price is the error,"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4ce7587f-a8fe-41d2-a00b-9a2d6ab1ee43"],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox["\[Epsilon]", "MC"], "\[Tilde]", 
   FractionBox[
    RowBox[{"\[Sigma]", "(", "f", ")"}], 
    SqrtBox["N"]], "=", 
   RowBox[{"O", "(", 
    SuperscriptBox["N", 
     RowBox[{"-", "1", "/", "2"}]], ")"}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormula",ExpressionUUID->"84ebed5b-e6d0-4641-\
9608-47363f220dbd"],

Cell["\<\
Halving the error means quadrupling the work; one more decimal digit costs a \
hundredfold. When each sample is an expensive model solve, that square-root \
wall is the entire problem. Its cause is visible: random points clump and \
leave gaps, wasting information. What if we placed them on purpose?\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"aa987c9f-f2a3-4b48-8b55-6f1d0656423d"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
mc  = LDPoints[\"MonteCarlo\", 256, 2];
hal = LDPoints[\"Halton\", 256, 2];
sob = LDPoints[\"Sobol\", 256, 2];
GraphicsRow[ListPlot[#, AspectRatio -> 1, Frame -> True,
   PlotRange -> {{0, 1}, {0, 1}}, ImageSize -> 230] & /@ {mc, hal, sob}]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"415bef87-36c5-44d5-b9ae-b141a6f4b40f"],

