Cell[TextData[{
 "Figure 3.  Same data, two philosophies. ",
 StyleBox["Left:",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " least squares returns a single best-fit curve \[LongDash] and, because the \
model is unidentifiable here, no usable error band. ",
 StyleBox["Right:",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " the Bayesian posterior (sampled by QMC) delivers a full predictive band; \
the lognormal priors gently regularize the directions the data cannot \
constrain."
}], "Text",
 CellMargins->{{45, 40}, {2, 14}},
 FontSize->11.5,
 FontSlant->Italic,
 FontColor->GrayLevel[
  0.4],ExpressionUUID->"414dead9-3d2e-4e71-a97e-910c0fffd238"],

Cell["\<\
The Bayesian posterior fixes this honestly: the priors keep the \
weakly-identified directions finite, and the answer is a full joint \
distribution \[LongDash] every parameter, every prediction, with calibrated \
uncertainty. The catch is the one from \[Section]4: you must integrate. The \
options:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"701d8a45-de44-40ae-a1b8-bb31d89bcb24"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Grid quadrature",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " \[LongDash] exact-ish in 1\[Dash]2 dimensions, hopeless in six (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"10", " ", "points", "/", "dim"}], TraditionalForm]], 
  "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->"56c8727d-971c-4bc0-a87f-1a4b2386b75f"],
 " is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["10", "6"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"281f846f-bb4e-4981-8af7-feb695a92c6b"],
 " evaluations, and the accuracy is still poor)."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"a5cb040a-927b-473a-8251-49f51c3c0932"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Markov-chain Monte Carlo (MCMC)",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " \[LongDash] the standard Bayesian workhorse; it samples the posterior \
directly but inherits the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["N", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1", "/", "2"}]], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"9527432f-5066-4d9c-b99d-931024d28e60"],
 " Monte-Carlo rate (worse, after autocorrelation) and needs tuning and \
convergence checks."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"4f90deac-8e08-41a9-9ceb-ad16a106d688"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Laplace approximation",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " \[LongDash] fit a Gaussian at the posterior mode; cheap, and the basis we \
build on here."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"76dcafd7-6be4-4105-982d-6d04f4119a83"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Quasi-Monte Carlo",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " \[LongDash] deterministic low-discrepancy points, near ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["N", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "a29178b4-7eca-4706-a2c6-56dd00583a12"],
 " for smooth integrands. For moderate-dimensional, smooth posteriors it is \
the most evaluations-efficient of the lot \[LongDash] and it is a drop-in \
replacement for the random draws."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c15d75f9-9de9-4551-8554-7038c13488be"],

Cell["\<\
QMC does not compete with MCMC so much as complement it: where you can \
reparameterize the posterior to be smooth and roughly Gaussian (Bayesian \
asymptotics says you usually can), QMC integration buys back most of the lost \
power. That is the recipe we follow next.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ab29a33c-237c-4b5e-9d1a-7b5212a4b050"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["6.  The fit", "Section",
 FontColor->RGBColor[
  0.153, 0.51, 0.64],ExpressionUUID->"8dd40655-5bd8-4bd4-81f1-94947bbba2f5"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["From posterior to a unit-cube integral.",
  FontSlant->Italic],
 " We build the ",
 StyleBox["Laplace\[Dash]Gaussian",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " approximation \[LongDash] posterior mode plus curvature in log-parameter \
space, a multivariate normal ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"N", "(", "\[Mu]", ",", "\[CapitalSigma]", ")"}], 
   TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "df41bfe4-29bd-4a05-8138-d57679e374a2"],
 " on ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[CurlyPhi]", "=", 
    RowBox[{"log", " ", "\[Theta]"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineFormula",
  ExpressionUUID->"a84c607e-3cc4-47c8-8426-1619281e61a3"],
 " \[LongDash] and map the unit cube onto it with the inverse-CDF transform \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[CurlyPhi]", "(", "u", ")", "=", 
    RowBox[{"\[Mu]", "+", 
     RowBox[{"L", " ", 
      SuperscriptBox["\[CapitalPhi]", 
       RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], "(", "u", ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], 
  "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->"24f6550e-a3d7-4881-9afb-5fc7207acc87"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"L", 
    SuperscriptBox["L", "T"], "=", "\[CapitalSigma]"}], TraditionalForm]], 
  "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->"fa654323-1c54-43d9-8f48-675dc4a60421"],
 ". A posterior expectation becomes an integral over ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"[", "0", ",", "1", "]"}], "6"], TraditionalForm]], 
  "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->"4eb22681-f7d1-498f-9b5b-d2c59e7d7be9"],
 " of a smooth, weight-free integrand \[LongDash] ready for QMC."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7aaba0ee-73a6-4524-ad21-f2fa462dda60"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
(* Draw from the posterior with a Sobol' set; form the predictive band *)
draws  = PosteriorDraws[LDPoints[\"Sobol\", 4096, 6], pkLaplace];
tGrid  = Subdivide[0., 25., 200];
curves = ConcentrationCurves[draws, tGrid, subj1[\"dose\"]];
band   = Transpose[curves];
{Quantile[#, 0.05] & /@ band, Quantile[#, 0.95] & /@ band};\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"8d288f9d-5bd6-4165-9ae6-2a0dbe6692ff"],

